  "title": "Cardiovascular physiology: CVP waveform",
  "body_html": "<div>Jugular venous pressure (JVP) may be assessed clinically and gives the clinician information regarding the patient's central venous pressure (CVP) during the cardiac cycle.<br /><br />The normal CVP waveform has 3 positive deflections or waves (a, c, v) and 2 descents  (x, y):<br /><ul><li>The 'a' wave occurs during contraction of the right atrium</li><li>The 'c' wave occurs during early ventricular contraction due to the tricuspid valve bulging in to the right atrium. It corresponds to isovolumetric contraction of the right ventricle</li><li>The 'v' wave is due to an increase in atrial pressure before opening of the tricuspid valve.  It corresponds to atrial filling</li><li>The 'x' descent is due to relaxation of the atrium</li><li>The 'y' descent happens during the emptying of the right atria and rapid filling of the right ventricle</li></ul><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti498b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti498.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>The CVP waveform </div><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti497b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti497.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating the CVP waveform in relation to the cardiac cycle and ECG. <b>Click on image to enlarge</b> </div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"><table><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a href=\"#\" class=\"media_link\" data-url=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5tUWOF6wEnk\" data-description=\"Cardiac cycle animation\" data-media=\"54\"><img border=\"0\" alt=\"YouTube\" src=\"https://i1.ytimg.com/vi/5tUWOF6wEnk/mqdefault.jpg\" style=\"max-width:150px;\"></a></td></tr><tr ><td style=\"padding-top:10px\" colspan=\"2\"><a style=\"\" href=\"#\" class=\"media_link\" data-url=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5tUWOF6wEnk\" data-media=\"54\">Cardiac cycle animation</a></td></tr><tr><td><span ><small> LUXSONTube - YouTube</small></span></td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"media_like_73\" data-mediaid=\"73\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-media btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"media_good_count_73\" class = \"media_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"media_dislike_73\" data-mediaid=\"73\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-media btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"media_bad_count_73\" class = \"media_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr></table></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">2</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">2</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Physiology</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Cardiovascular physiology</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\nJugular venous pressure (JVP) may be assessed clinically and gives the clinician information regarding the patient's central venous pressure (CVP) during the cardiac cycle.<br /><br />The normal CVP waveform has 3 positive deflections or waves (a, c, v) and 2 descents  (x, y):<br /><ul><li>The 'a' wave occurs during contraction of the right atrium</li><li>The 'c' wave occurs during early ventricular contraction due to the tricuspid valve bulging in to the right atrium. It corresponds to isovolumetric contraction of the right ventricle</li><li>The 'v' wave is due to an increase in atrial pressure before opening of the tricuspid valve.  It corresponds to atrial filling</li><li>The 'x' descent is due to relaxation of the atrium</li><li>The 'y' descent happens during the emptying of the right atria and rapid filling of the right ventricle</li></ul><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti498b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti498.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>The CVP waveform </div><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti497b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti497.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating the CVP waveform in relation to the cardiac cycle and ECG. <b>Click on image to enlarge</b> </div></div>\n\n\n<BR><BR><br><br><table><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a href=\"#\" class=\"media_link\" data-url=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5tUWOF6wEnk\" data-description=\"Cardiac cycle animation\" data-media=\"54\"><img border=\"0\" alt=\"YouTube\" src=\"https://i1.ytimg.com/vi/5tUWOF6wEnk/mqdefault.jpg\" style=\"max-width:150px;\"></a></td></tr><tr ><td style=\"padding-top:10px\" colspan=\"2\"><a style=\"\" href=\"#\" class=\"media_link\" data-url=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5tUWOF6wEnk\" data-media=\"54\">Cardiac cycle animation</a></td></tr><tr><td><span ><small> LUXSONTube - YouTube</small></span></td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"bu